<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/HeterogenousArray>
        a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy>
                <http://qudt.org/$$QUDT_VERSION$$/schema/datatype>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Heterogenous Array";
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/Array>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                [ a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction>;
                  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#cardinality>
                          1;
                  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperty>
                          <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/datatype>
                ];
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                [ a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction>;
                  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#minCardinality>
                          1;
                  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperty>
                          <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/datatype>
                ];
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                [ a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction>;
                  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#maxCardinality>
                          1;
                  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperty>
                          <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/datatype>
                ];
        <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description>
                "\n  <p>An <em>Array></em> is a data structure that stores a collection of elements, typically of the same type, in a contiguous block of memory. \n  Each element in an array is identified by an index or key, which is typically a numerical identifier, either starting at '0' or '1'.\n  </p>\n  <p>The key considerations for an Array are:\n  </p>\n  <ol>\n  <li>Fixed Size: The size of an array may be pre-determined when it is created and cannot be changed;</li>\n  <li>Index-Based Access: Elements can be accessed, updated, or modified using their index;</li>\n  <li>Heterogenous Elements: all elements in the array may be of different data types;</li>\n  <li>Contiguous Memory Allocation: \n    the elements are stored in consecutive memory locations, which allows efficient access using the index.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <p>An Array is represented as ordered entries of values arranged according to its dimensionality.\n  The number of dimensions is specified in the attribute 'dimensionality'.\n  </p>\n  <p>The property 'qudt:datatype' refers to a list if the datatypes of the elements.  \n  </p>\n  <p>An heterogenous array can be multi-dimensional.\n  Multiple indices are used but they are treated as extensions of the same structure.\n  For example: for a 2D array arr[2][3], indices refer to the row and column positions.\n  A 2D array is still represented as a list, where each member of the list is a list.\n  </p>\n  <p>Higher dimensional arrays can be represented as nested lists.\n  For each dimension a new nested list is defined.\n  </p>"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .

<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/TextStringType>
        a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class>;
