<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/Heap>
        a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy>
                <http://qudt.org/$$QUDT_VERSION$$/schema/datatype>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Heap";
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/OrderedTree>;
        <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description>
                "\n  <p>A heap is a specialized tree-based data structure that satisfies the condition: if B is a child node of A, then $key(A) \\ge key(B)$. \n  This implies that an element with the greatest key is always in the root node, and so such a heap is sometimes called a max heap. \n  Alternatively, if the comparison is reversed, the smallest element is always in the root node, which results in a min heap. \n  The function or method that implements the key() operator is specified by the heap type.\n  </p>"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML>;
        <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasInfluencedBy>
                <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heap_(data_structure)> .

