<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/SinglePrecisionType>
        a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy>
                <http://qudt.org/$$QUDT_VERSION$$/schema/datatype>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Single Precision Type";
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/NumericType>;
        <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description>
                "\n  A single precision data type specifies how a numeric value, such as an integer or real number,\n   is stored in memory that occupies one word in computer memory,\n   where the byte length of a word depends on machine address size of the computer processor. \n  For example, on 32-bit machine architectures, a word is four bytes.\n  A single precision data value on a 32-bit machine architecture occupies four bytes of memory.\n  " .

<http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/ShortIntegerType>
        a       <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy>
                <http://qudt.org/$$QUDT_VERSION$$/schema/datatype>;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Short Integer Type";
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf>
                <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/IntegerDatatype>;
        <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description>
                "\n  A Short Integer is an integer that can be represented in two octets (16 bits) of machine memory. \n  Short integers may be signed or unsigned.\n  " .

